TITLE: Can Congress Use an Archaic Process to Get Around the Debt Stalemate?
SUMMARY: Some Democrats are urging their colleagues to lay the groundwork for using an arcane procedural process to bypass Republicans and stave off economic peril.

TITLE: Jobs Report Bolsters Biden’s Economic Pitch, but Inflation Still Nags
SUMMARY: The president is framing slower employment growth as the basis of a new stability, not a harbinger of hard times.

TITLE: U.S. Job Growth Eases, but Extends Its Streak
SUMMARY: Employers added 236,000 jobs as the Federal Reserve’s interest-rate increases appeared to take a toll. The unemployment rate fell to 3.5 percent.

TITLE: How AI and DNA Are Unlocking the Mysteries of Global Supply Chains
SUMMARY: Firms are turning to advanced technologies to help answer a surprisingly tricky question: Where do products really come from?

TITLE: Wages May Not Be Inflation’s Cause, but They’re the Focus of the Cure
SUMMARY: While fear of a “wage-price spiral” has eased, the Federal Reserve’s course presumes job losses and risks a recession. Some see less painful remedies.

TITLE: I.R.S. Unveils $80 Billion Plan to Overhaul Tax Collection
SUMMARY: The 10-year strategy document outlines a focus on improving customer service and cracking down on tax evasion by corporations and the wealthy.

TITLE: In Ohio, Electric Cars Are Starting to Reshape Jobs and Companies
SUMMARY: The state, heavily dependent on the auto industry, is a case study in whether electric vehicles will create or destroy jobs.

TITLE: Job Openings Fell in February, JOLTS Report Shows
SUMMARY: The U.S. job market continues to ease off its red-hot pace, a government report shows, but there are still more openings than unemployed workers.

TITLE: Auto Sales Withstand Higher Interest Rates, So Far
SUMMARY: General Motors and several rivals cited robust demand in the first quarter. But affordability is a growing challenge for many buyers.

TITLE: Biden’s Reluctant Approach to Free Trade Draws Backlash
SUMMARY: A law intended to bolster clean energy manufacturing has ignited debate over whether the U.S. should work to break down international trade barriers — or keep them intact to protect American workers.

TITLE: Noncompete Clauses Get Tighter, and TV Newsrooms Feel the Grip
SUMMARY: Job-switching barriers are routine at TV stations, even for workers not on the air. A proposed federal rule would curb the practice across all fields.

TITLE: How a Trump-Era Rollback Mattered for Silicon Valley Bank’s Demise
SUMMARY: An under-the-radar change to the way regional banks are supervised may have helped the bank’s rapidly growing risks to go unresolved.

TITLE: Top Economist Leaves White House, and an Economy Not Yet ‘Normal’
SUMMARY: Cecilia Rouse says lingering effects of the coronavirus pandemic continue to haunt the recovery from recession — and drag on Americans’ optimism for the economy.

TITLE: The Fed’s Preferred Inflation Gauge Cooled Notably in February
SUMMARY: A closely watched measure of price increases provided encouraging news as the Fed considers when to stop raising rates.

TITLE: Do We Know How Many People Are Working From Home?
SUMMARY: New Labor Department numbers indicate that fewer Americans worked remotely last year. But many experts criticize the government’s data collection.

TITLE: Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Spars With Democrats at Senate Hearing
SUMMARY: Howard Schultz faced rancor from Senate Democrats at a hearing where he chafed at “propaganda that is floating around” about company labor practices.

TITLE: Top Fed Officials Criticize Silicon Valley Bank Executives at Senate Hearing
SUMMARY: Officials blamed executives at Silicon Valley Bank for its failure on March 10, while adding that Federal Reserve oversight is in for a revamp.

TITLE: Biden Highlights Economic Investments Ahead of Expected 2024 Announcement
SUMMARY: The president has warned that a strong economy could be weakened under Republican leadership, a point he and a host of advisers will make at 20 events across the country in the coming weeks.

TITLE: SVB Hearing Takeaways: Bank Failures Spur a Blame Game, But Few Solutions
SUMMARY: Senators sharply questioned federal regulators about shortcomings in oversight after two bank failures rattled the financial system. Regulators put the blame on the banks’ management.

TITLE: Lawmakers Rebuke Biden for Bypassing Congress in Trade Deal With Japan
SUMMARY: A statement from two Democrats called the Biden administration’s deal “unacceptable,” saying it should have been made available to Congress and the public for review.
